{
  "query": "Explain the rules for building Houses and Hotels, including when they can be bought and any building limits.",
  "answer": "To build Houses and Hotels in Monopoly, you must first own all Sites of a color-group to buy Houses. You can purchase Houses on your turn or between other players' turns but must build evenly: one House per Site before building another.\n\nFor buying Hotels, you need four Houses on each Site of a complete color-group. Only one Hotel may be erected on any one Site. The Bank will pay half the cash price of the Hotel plus half the price of the four Houses that were given to the Bank for the purchase of the Hotel. All Hotels on one color-group can be sold at once.\n\nThere are no specific building limits mentioned for Houses, but you cannot build a second House on any Site until you have built one House on every Site of that group, and so on up to a maximum of four Houses per Site. Selling Houses must be done evenly as well: selling a House reduces the number by one, allowing you to buy another later.\n\nRegarding Hotels, if there are no Houses left in the Bank, you must wait for other players to return theirs before buying any. When selling Hotels, you cannot replace them with Houses if there are Houses available. Mortgaged Property cannot be sold to the Bank, but can be sold to other players only.",
  "sources": [
    {
      "file": "docs/monopoly.pdf",
      "page": 5,
      "section_path": [
        "THE PROPERTY TRADING BOARD GAME",
        "RULES"
      ],
      "element_type": "paragraph",
      "score": 0.032786883,
      "excerpt": "Hotels You must have four Houses on each Site of a complete colour-group before you can buy a Hotel. Hotels are bought in the same way as Houses and cost four Houses, which are returned to the Bank,…"
    },
    {
      "file": "docs/monopoly.pdf",
